PART 8 : ERRORS AND DEBUGGING
Error 1: Feature Count Mismatch Between Training and Tuning Scripts
Exact issue:
When running train_session.py, the drop_cols list was configured to keep 101 features. However, the tuning script imported the same class but had a different version of drop_cols (perhaps an older branch), resulting in only 85 features being used. The hyperparameters found by the tuning script were therefore optimised for a different feature space than the one they were applied to.

Symptom:
After applying the best hyperparameters (nu=0.2, gamma=0.00055, threshold=-0.3) to the main training script, accuracy actually dropped instead of improving.

Root cause:
gamma is sensitive to the number of features. A value that works for 85 features may be completely wrong for 101 features. Additionally, the feature sets themselves were different, so the tuned hyperparameters were not transferable.

Fix attempted / final solution:

Ensure that the drop_cols list in train_session.py is locked before running any tuning script.

The tuning script imports SessionOCSVM directly from train_session, so both scripts use exactly the same feature selection.

Always run the tuning script after finalising the drop_cols list.

Current status: ✅ Resolved. Both scripts now share the same class and feature set.

Error 2: Hardcoded Decision Threshold
Exact error:
In SessionOCSVM.evaluate(), the prediction line was:

python
y_pred = np.where(scores >= 0, 1, -1)
The threshold was hardcoded to 0, regardless of the tuned value.

Symptom:
Even after the hyperparameter tuning script selected threshold=-0.3 as optimal, the main training script continued using 0. TAR showed no improvement (or very little) after tuning because the threshold was never actually changed.

Root cause:
The evaluate method did not read the threshold from a variable; it was a literal 0 in the code.

Fix applied:
Changed to:

python
threshold = -0.3   # or set from a variable
y_pred = np.where(scores >= threshold, 1, -1)
Lesson: Always verify that tuned hyperparameters are actually injected into every part of the code.

Current status: ✅ Resolved. The threshold is now explicitly set.

Error 3: MFCC and Multitaper Methods Defined but Never Called
Exact issue:
The methods _extract_mfcc_features and _extract_multitaper_features were written and placed inside SessionLevelFeatureExtractor, but inside extract_fft_features, only _extract_windowed_fft was called for acc_mag and gyro_mag. The new methods were never invoked.

Symptom:
After regenerating the feature CSVs, no new columns (like acc_mag_mfcc_0_mean) appeared. The team observed no accuracy change when using the new CSVs – because the features were simply not present.

Root cause:
The code for calling the new methods was missing from extract_fft_features.

Fix applied:
Updated extract_fft_features to call:

python
features.update(self._extract_mfcc_features(acc_mag_active, 'acc_mag', fs))
features.update(self._extract_multitaper_features(acc_mag_active, 'acc_mag', fs))
# ... similarly for each axis
Current status: ✅ Resolved. The extended CSVs now contain the new frequency‑domain features.

Error 4: Methods Defined Inside Other Methods (Indentation)
Exact issue:
In the pasted code for SessionLevelFeatureExtractor, many methods were indented one level too deep, placing them inside the body of the previous method. For example, extract_touch_sensor_features appeared to be inside extract_gyro_features.

Symptom:
Running the feature extraction would raise AttributeError: 'SessionLevelFeatureExtractor' object has no attribute 'extract_touch_sensor_features' when that method was called from extract_session_features.

Root cause:
A copy‑paste or editing error introduced extra indentation.

Fix applied:
All methods were re‑indented to be direct children of the class (one 4‑space indent). This was done manually in the final corrected file.

Current status: ✅ Resolved. The class structure is now correct.

Error 5: Variable Name Typo e → s
Exact error:
Inside extract_fused_touch_sensor_features, the loop iterates over sensor_events using for s in sensor_events:, but inside the loop there was a line:

python
ts = e.get("timestamp")
