Error 6: Inconsistent Key Casing – _fft_defaults vs _extract_windowed_fft
Exact issue:
_extract_windowed_fft returns keys like f'{prefix}_fft_band_low_0_2hz' (lowercase hz).
The original _fft_defaults method (before correction) used f'{prefix}_fft_band_low_0_2Hz' (capital H).
This mismatch would cause KeyError or missing columns when the early‑return path was triggered.

Fix applied:
Unified all keys to use lowercase hz. The corrected _fft_defaults now accepts a prefix argument and generates the same keys as _extract_windowed_fft.

Current status: ✅ Resolved.

Error 7: Incorrect Gamma Candidates in Tuning Script
Exact error (in earlier version of tuning script):

python
gamma_candidates = [FIXED_GAMMA * mult / n_features for mult in GAMMA_MULTIPLIERS]
This multiplied the fixed gamma by the multiplier, producing extremely small values (e.g., 0.00055 * 0.1 / 85 ≈ 6.5e-7). The desired adaptive gamma values (like mult / n_features) were never actually tested. The reported “best” gamma of 0.00055 could not have come from this list – it was probably a copy‑paste error.

Fix applied:
Changed to:

python
gamma_candidates = [FIXED_GAMMA] + [mult / n_features for mult in GAMMA_MULTIPLIERS]
Current status: ✅ Resolved in tune_louo_expanded.py.

Error 8: Global Tuning Overfits to Test Set
Issue:
The global tuning script (tune_global.py) trained each user on their own training data and tested on their own test data, then averaged the TAR and selected the best hyperparameters. This directly optimises on the test set.

Symptom:
The reported TAR during tuning was high, but when the same parameters were used in the main script (or on new users), performance dropped.

Root cause:
Test data was used for hyperparameter selection, violating the principle that test data must remain unseen.

Fix:
Switched to Leave‑One‑User‑Out (LOUO) tuning, where each user serves as the test set exactly once, and the hyperparameters are chosen based on cross‑validated performance.

Current status: ✅ LOUO tuning is the standard method. Global tuning is only kept for rough exploration and is clearly documented as biased.

Error 9: Missing Default Keys in Early‑Return Dictionaries
Issue:
When a session has too few touches or sensors, the extraction methods return a small default dictionary (e.g., only 5 keys). After the feature extraction was expanded (MFCC, multitaper, per‑axis, swipe geometry), the early‑return paths did not include the new keys.

Symptom:
When concatenating sessions into a single CSV, sessions that hit the early‑return path would have NaN for all the new columns. This caused column misalignment and potentially corrupted the feature matrix.

Fix applied:
Introduced _all_fft_defaults() that returns a complete dictionary with zero values for every possible feature key. The early‑return paths now use this master default dictionary. Similarly, extract_touch_features early return was updated to include all possible touch keys (including swipe geometry).

Current status: ✅ Resolved. All sessions now produce a consistent column set.

Error 10: fillna(0) vs fillna(median)
Issue:
The original training script used np.nan_to_num (which fills with 0). Zero imputation can distort distributions, especially for features like stft_entropy or gyro_std where zero is not a natural baseline.

Fix applied:
Phase 1 and the tuning scripts now use median imputation. The main train_session.py still uses np.nan_to_num for simplicity, but the tuned hyperparameters were obtained on median‑imputed data. For consistency, the main script should eventually also use median imputation.

Current status: ⚠️ Partially resolved – median imputation is used in all data‑cleaning and tuning steps; the main script is noted for future update.

Error 11: Bare except: in extract_long_acc_gyro
Issue:
The code contained a bare except: clause that would silently swallow any error, including typos or shape mismatches. This made debugging nearly impossible.

Fix:
Replaced with except Exception: and added a print statement (recommendation). In the final version, specific exceptions should be caught.

Current status: ⚠️ Recommended but not yet applied in the provided code. Documented for future cleanup.

Error 12: SMA and Correlations Computed Inside Axis Loop
Issue:
In extract_acc_features_mag_window, the SMA and the correlation coefficients (xy_corr, xz_corr, yz_corr) were computed inside the for axis_name, signal in axis_data.items(): loop. This means they were computed once for each axis (x, y, z, mag), even though the values are identical each time. Not a correctness bug, but inefficient and confusing.

Fix:
Moved the four lines outside the axis loop, so they run only once per window.

Current status: ✅ Fixed in the corrected code.

Error 13: DTW Template File Not Found
Issue:
When running SessionPipeline.run(), the script tries to load {user_id}_dtw_templates.pkl from the templates/ folder. If the file doesn't exist, it prints a warning and sets centroids, medoids = None, None. Later code raises ValueError("DTW templates not found").

Symptom:
Feature extraction fails for users without pre‑computed DTW templates.

Fix:
Ensure DTW templates are generated before running the pipeline. This is a prerequisite, not a bug.

Current status: ✅ Documented as a dependency.

Error 14: The “Combination Pitfall” – Two Good Subsets Decrease TAR When Merged
Exact issue:
The team found two independent feature subsets that each improved TAR by a few percent. When both subsets were combined (uncommented from drop_cols simultaneously), TAR decreased below the baseline.

Root cause:
The OCSVM hyperparameters were optimised for the original feature set. Adding features changes the effective dimensionality, making the old nu, gamma, and threshold sub‑optimal. Additionally, new features might be highly correlated with existing ones, introducing redundancy.

Lesson:

Always re‑tune hyperparameters after changing the feature set.

Check for multicollinearity (Spearman correlation > 0.95) before combining subsets.

Use the LOUO tuning script to evaluate each new combination honestly.

Current status: ✅ Understood. The LOUO tuning script is designed to handle this automatically.

Error 15: Feature count mismatch for user X
Symptom:
During LOUO data loading, an AssertionError is raised because one user’s training CSV has a different number of columns than the others.

Possible causes:

Different versions of the feature extraction code were used for different users.

Some CSVs are from an older run (before MFCC/multitaper were added).

Fix:
Re‑generate all CSVs with the latest version of SessionLevelFeatureExtractor. Ensure the same drop_cols and method calls are used for every user.

Current status: ✅ Resolved by regenerating CSVs from a single code version.

Debugging Discussions Summary
Throughout the project, the following debugging techniques were used or recommended:

Printing feature counts (len(self.feature_columns)) to verify the correct feature set is loaded.

Inspecting CSV columns after regeneration to confirm new features are present.

Plotting score scatter plots per user to visually check separation of genuine and impostor.

Checking validation FRR via the validate() method to detect overfitting.

Saving full grid search results to CSV for inspection (instead of relying only on the printed best).

Comparing global tuning vs LOUO tuning results to detect overfitting.

Verifying that tuned hyperparameters are actually hardcoded in the final script before running.

